  },
  {
    label: 'Harvard Health: Relaxation techniques: Breath control helps quell errant stress response',
    href: 'https://www.health.harvard.edu/mind-and-mood/relaxation-techniques-breath-control-helps-quell-errant-stress-response',
  },
  {
    label: 'WHO: Doing What Matters in Times of Stress',
    href: 'https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789240003927',
  },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  lang="en"
  altPath="/blog/bai-tap-tho-khi-hoi-hop/"
  title="Breathing exercises for anxiety: how to settle in a minute | An Nhịp"
  description="Two breathing exercises for anxiety: belly breathing (inhale 4 seconds, exhale 6 seconds) and box breathing. Clear steps, common mistakes, and when to get more support."
  heading="Breathing exercises for anxiety: how to settle in a minute"
  datePublished="2026-07-21"
  sources={sources}
>
  <p>
    Your heart is racing, your chest feels tight, your hands are a little shaky.
    If that is where you are right now, try the steps below before you read the
    explanation that follows.
  </p>

  <h2>Try this now: one minute of slow breathing</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Sit or stand in a comfortable position. If you can, let your shoulders drop.</li>
    <li>Breathe in through your nose, slowly, counting 1, 2, 3, 4.</li>
    <li>Breathe out gently through your mouth or nose, counting 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6.</li>
    <li>Repeat about 6 times, which is roughly one minute.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The most important part: <strong>make your out-breath longer than your
    in-breath</strong>. You do not need to count perfectly. Just keep the rhythm
    slow and even. If you feel dizzy, stop and breathe normally.
  </p>

  <h2>Why slow breathing helps your body settle</h2>
  <p>
    When you feel anxious, your body switches on its stress response: your heart
    beats faster, and your breathing gets quicker and shallower. That is a normal
    reaction, not a sign that you are "weak". Slow, deep breathing works in the
    opposite direction. It activates the parasympathetic nervous system, the part
    that helps your body rest, so your heart rate and that keyed-up feeling can
    gradually ease. Self-care guides from the NHS and Harvard Health both list
    slow breathing among the most basic and easiest to learn relaxation
    techniques.
  </p>
  <p>
    In other words, there is no way to instantly stop anxiety, and that is not
    the goal. The goal is to lower the intensity enough that you can think
    clearly again.
  </p>

  <h2>Belly breathing: your everyday foundation</h2>
  <p>
    Belly breathing (diaphragmatic breathing) uses the diaphragm, letting your
    belly rise as you breathe in instead of lifting your shoulders and chest.
    Here is how:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>Put one hand on your belly and one hand on your chest.</li>
    <li>Breathe in through your nose for 4 seconds, letting the hand on your belly be pushed up while the hand on your chest stays almost still.</li>
    <li>Breathe out slowly for 6 seconds, letting your belly fall naturally.</li>
    <li>Do not hold your breath between breaths. Practice for 3 to 5 minutes.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    This is a good exercise to practice every day while you are calm, for example
    before you fall asleep. Practicing when it is easy is what makes it usable
    when it is hard: once your body knows this rhythm, it finds its way back to
    it faster when you feel anxious.
  </p>

  <h2>Box breathing: when you need a structure to hold onto</h2>
  <p>
    Box breathing splits your breath into four equal sides of 4 seconds each:
    breathe in for 4 seconds, hold for 4 seconds, breathe out for 4 seconds, hold
    for 4 seconds. The steady counting gives your mind one concrete thing to do,
    so this style suits moments when your thoughts are racing and you need a
    clear rhythm to hold onto.
  </p>
  <p>
    If 4 seconds per side is too long for you, start with 3 seconds. The right
    pace is the one you can keep comfortably, not the one in a book.
  </p>

  <h2>Common mistakes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Trying to breathe in very deeply, very fast.</strong> Straining to
      breathe in can easily make you dizzy. Slow matters more than deep.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Breathing with your chest and shoulders.</strong> If your shoulders
      rise with every breath, go back to belly breathing with a hand on your
      belly.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Giving up after one round.</strong> The effect usually comes after
      about a minute or more, so give your body enough time.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Using the exercise to "fight" your anxiety.</strong> The harder you
      push the feeling to go away, the more it clings. Treat the exercise as a
      way of staying with your own body, not as a weapon.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When breathing is not enough</h2>
  <p>
    Breathing exercises are a tool for turning the intensity down on the spot,
    not a treatment. If anxiety shows up often, lasts for weeks, or affects your
    sleep, work, or relationships, you deserve professional support from a doctor
    or a mental health professional. Reaching out early is an act of self-care,
    not a failure.
  </p>

